Curse of dimensionality¶

Calculate distances in all dimensions for Cars93 data and plot the histogram

In [80]:
Copied! 
Distance <-  as.vector(as.matrix( dist(X[,1]) ))
L <- length(Distance)
Dimension <- rep(1, L)
Ndim <- dim(X)[2]
for(n in 2:Ndim){
    Distance <- c(Distance, as.vector(as.matrix( dist(X[,1:n]) )))
    Dimension <- c(Dimension, rep(n, L))
    }
Distance <- as.vector(as.matrix( dist(X[,1]) )) L <- length(Distance) Dimension <- rep(1, L) Ndim <- dim(X)[2] for(n in 2:Ndim){ Distance <- c(Distance, as.vector(as.matrix( dist(X[,1:n]) ))) Dimension <- c(Dimension, rep(n, L)) }

Kernel PCA¶

is contained in the package kernlab. Try out other kernel types beyond the gaussian one. Type help(kpca) to see how to use the options. Remember to standardize the data first. other packages do that internally.

Linear Discriminant Analysis¶

contained in the MASS package. The functions run a regression based on the projection,so we provide prior probabilities for each class (they give weight to each class). formula = Type ~ Price+MPG.city+MPG.highway+Length+Wheelbase+Width+Turn.circle+Weight means that those numeric variables are part of the regression (projection) against the Type. Note we do not use all variables (some are probably collinear, like the price and the maximum price).

In [134]:
Copied! 
Y_lda <- lda(formula = Type ~ Price+MPG.city+MPG.highway+Length+Wheelbase+Width+Turn.circle+Weight, 
          data = Cars93)
Y_lda <- lda(formula = Type ~ Price+MPG.city+MPG.highway+Length+Wheelbase+Width+Turn.circle+Weight, data = Cars93)

We calculate those features using some good old vectorization in R. First take the coefficients, Then multiply by the data and do the sum by rows.

In [296]:
Copied! 
LD <- list()
Ndim <- dim(Y_lda$scaling)[2]
for(n in 1:Ndim){
    coeff_LD <- matrix(rep(Y_lda$scaling[,paste("LD",n,sep="")],dim(X)[1]),
       nrow=dim(X)[1], byrow=T)
    LD[[n]] <- rowSums(X * coeff_LD)
}
LD <- list() Ndim <- dim(Y_lda$scaling)[2] for(n in 1:Ndim){ coeff_LD <- matrix(rep(Y_lda$scaling[,paste("LD",n,sep="")],dim(X)[1]), nrow=dim(X)[1], byrow=T) LD[[n]] <- rowSums(X * coeff_LD) }

Non-parametric methods¶

tSNE¶

From the code in the book or your own improved code.

Run your personal tSNE function (in my case sam_tsne) or the one from the book (casl_tsne). Here init, momentum and early_ex are not options found in casl_tsne
